doc.ContractDescription: MUCH OF THE LAST 15 YEARS' PROGRESS TOWARD UNDERSTANDING THE ORIGIN, EVOLUTION, AND FATE OF OUR UNIVERSE HAS BEEN ACCOMPLISHED BY MEASURING THE LARGE-SCALE FLUCTUATIONS IN THE UNIVERSE, AND IN COMING YEARS WE CAN EXPECT PROJECTS SUCH AS THE JOINT DARK ENERGY MISSION TO INCREASE THE QUANTITY AND QUALITY OF LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURE DATA BY 2 TO 3 ORDERS OF MAGNITUDE. IT IS ALSO CLEAR THAT FLUCTUATIONS IN THE METRIC POTENTIALS OF THE UNIVERSE WILL PROVIDE HIGH-PRECISION TESTS OF THE NATURE OF GRAVITY ON SCALES BEYOND THE SOLAR SYSTEM. IN COMING YEARS, GRAVITATIONAL LENSING AND GALAXY CLUSTER OBSERVATIONS WILL JOIN FAMILIAR GALAXY REDSHIFT SURVEYS IN TRACING LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURE OVER LARGE FRACTIONS OF THE SKY. THESE OBSERVATIONAL EFFORTS WILL NOT REACH THEIR FULL POTENTIAL WITHOUT BETTER UNDERSTANDING HOW THE DISTRIBUTION OF GALAXIES AND DARK MATTER HALOS IN THE UNIVERSE RELATES TO THE UNDERLYING MASS DISTRIBUTION. CURRENT METHODS FOR USING GALAXY OBSERVATIONS TO ESTIMATE THE DENSITY AND VELOCITY OF THE UNDERLYING MASS DISTRIBUTION ASSUME SIMPLE POISSON DISTRIBUTIONS, WHICH ARE INCONSISTENT WITH NUMERICAL SIMULATIONS. WE WILL USE ANALYTIC AND NUMERICAL CALCULATIONS TO IMPROVE UNDERSTANDING OF THE STOCHASTIC RELATIONS BETWEEN GALAXIES AND MASS, WHICH WILL ALLOW OPTIMIZATION OF FUTURE NASA MISSIONS TO MEASURE THE LARGE-SCALE DISTRIBUTION OF DARK MATTER WITH GALAXY SURVEYS. GREATER INSIGHT INTO COSMOLOGY PARAMETERS, DARK ENERGY, AND THE EVOLUTION OF GALAXIES IS POSSIBLE BY COMBINING MULTIPLE PROBES OF LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURE---PARTICULARLY BY COMBINING GALAXY AND CLUSTER SURVEYS WITH GRAVITATIONAL LENSING, WHICH MEASURES GRAVITATIONAL POTENTIALS WITHOUT ASTROPHYSICAL BIASES. WE WILL INVESTIGATE THE POWER OF COMBINING MULTIPLE TRACERS OF LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURES AND VELOCITIES TO OBTAIN CONSTRAINTS MUCH STRONGER THAN THE SUM OF THEIR PARTS. SEVERAL POWERFUL CROSS-CORRELATION TESTS OF COSMOLOGY AND GENERAL RELATIVITY HAVE BEEN PROPOSED, AND THEIR ULTIMATE ACCURACY DEPENDS UPON THE NATURE OF STOCHASTICITY BETWEEN THESE TRACERS. WE WILL INVESTIGATE METHODS FOR CROSS-CORRELATIONS AND COMBINED ANALYSES OF LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURE PROBES, FORECAST THEIR POWER USING UPDATED MODELS OF STOCHASTICITY, AND SEEK NEW OPPORTUNITIES TO UNDERSTAND GRAVITY, DARK ENERGY, AND DARK MATTER USING LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURES. THESE RESULTS WILL GUIDE THE DESIGN AND INCREASE THE SCIENTIFIC POWER OF FUTURE NASA MISSIONS.
